{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501249"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:26:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:26:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1737"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1737","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1737"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.39,0.44,0.11,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1737"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111350"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1737","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1737"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1737"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93480"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3005"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3176"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3546"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10699"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11094"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111350","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111350"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents with a two week history of the intermittent and painless passage of blood in his urine. Over the last 12 months he has experienced increased urinary frequency, terminal dribbling and the need to void at least twice a night. He has a history of atrial fibrillation and type 2 diabetes mellitus. His medication history includes warfarin and metformin. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history and drinks two cans of beer a day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his blood pressure is 132/84 mmHg, pulse 80/min and temperature 37.4\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. Examination of the abdomen and pelvis is unremarkable, with no suprapubic dullness. Digital rectal examination finds a mildly enlarged soft prostate with the median sulcus well-defined.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine sediment reveals non distorted red cells but is otherwise unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Glomerulonephritis","Benign prostatic hyperplasia","Urothelial carcinoma","Renal cell carcinoma","Haemorrhagic cystitis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrothelial (bladder) carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E, previously known as transitional cell carcinoma is the most likely diagnosis. Painless haematuria is a \u003Cem\u003E\u2018red flag\u2019\u003C/em\u003E for malignancy, particularly in the setting of other risk factors such as smoking, male population and older age \u0026gt;50 years old. Urothelial carcinoma can present with both microscopic and gross haematuria, and less commonly with painful micturition, frequency and constitutional symptoms. Voided urine cytology is useful to look for malignant cells in this group of patients (haematuria in smokers).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal cell carcinoma \u003C/strong\u003Ecan also present with haematuria. However most cases are now incidental findings on imaging, with specific symptoms such as haematuria, abdominal or flank pain being quite unusual.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlomerulonephritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with red cell casts in the urine sediments, which were not present. Furthermore, glomerulonephritis may also present with proteinuria and hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBenign prostatic hyperplasia \u003C/strong\u003Epresents with urinary symptoms such as frequency and urgency. However, the presence of haematuria and absence of significant prostate-related findings on examination make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemorrhagic cystitis \u003C/strong\u003Eis diffuse inflammation of the bladder which can result in haematuria. However, this is often associated with infection, occupation exposure to chemicals such as (aniline and toluidine), chemotherapy and radiation near the bladder, which is not apparent in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Painless haematuria in an older man should be considered to have a malignant origin until proven otherwise."],"references":["Yaxley JP. Urinary tract cancers: An overview for general practice. J Family Med Prim Care. 2016;5(3):533-538. doi:10.4103/2249-4863.197258"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93480"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1737"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93480"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-13T08:43:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-13T08:43:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1737"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111350"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"de